      <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center mb-4">Real-World Use Cases</h2>
      <p class="text-center mb-6">Both frameworks are widely used in web development, but they tend to appear in different kinds of projects based on team needs and product goals.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Why Use Bootstrap?</h3>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
        <li>Fast MVPs and admin dashboards</li>
        <li>Enterprise software with consistent design</li>
        <li>Teams with minimal frontend design experience</li>
        <li>Legacy systems needing backward-compatible UI</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8">
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2">Why Use Tailwind CSS?</h3>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-4">
        <li>Custom UI for modern apps and startups</li>
        <li>Design systems that scale and evolve</li>
        <li>Agile teams with designers and developers working closely</li>
        <li>Projects requiring performance and minimal bloat</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
    <section class="mt-12">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4 text-center">Summary</h3>
      <p>Tailwind CSS is popular among developers seeking custom UIs with maximum flexibility, especially in startups, SaaS, and creative agencies. Bootstrap is ideal for traditional institutions and businesses that need fast, consistent interfaces with minimal design work.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8">
